Prompt: 'What is considered a high blood pressure reading?\n' 
Generated text: "It should be under 160/100.  I'm surprised you've never been tested.  It's normal for a doctor to do this when you're young and healthy.  But if you have a family history or are above a certain age, it is suggested you get it tested more often."

Prompt: 'What are the risks of having high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nThe risk of heart disease is 2 to 6 times greater if you have high blood pressure, compared to people with normal blood pressure.\n\nHigh blood pressure is usually caused by an imbalance in the amount of salt in the blood (sodium). When the kidneys excrete salt, some of it stays in the body to act as a buffer against the loss of sodium and fluids (water) from the body. If this buffer is depleted, it can cause high blood pressure.\n\nWhat causes high blood pressure?\n\nHigh blood pressure is the result of a build up of pressure in the arteries and veins. This is caused by a number of factors. These include:\n\nFamily history\n\nAged 65 years and over\n\nObesity\n\nFasting glucose\n\nSmoking\n\nAlcohol consumption\n\nCardiovascular disease is a major cause of mortality, especially in older people. The following are some risk factors for cardiovascular disease:\n\nFamily history\n\nAged 65 years and over\n\nObesity\n\nDiabetes mellitus\n\nAged 45 years and over\n\nSmoking\n\nAlcohol consumption\n\nHigh blood pressure is usually inherited. However, some people develop high blood pressure from other risk factors, such as smoking.\n\nWhat are the symptoms of high blood pressure?\n\nSymptoms of high blood pressure can include:\n\nFrequent urination\n\nDizziness\n\nDry mouth\n\nNausea\n\nFatigue\n\nChest pain\n\nSudden dizziness or fainting\n\nSweating\n\nBreathlessness\n\nHeadaches\n\nDifficulty concentrating\n\nTiredness\n\nHow is high blood pressure diagnosed?\n\nHigh blood pressure is often diagnosed with a blood pressure reading.\n\nA blood pressure reading is done by taking the blood pressure of one or both arms (usually the left arm) while lying flat on your back. You may need to stand up, sit down, or use a stethoscope.\n\nThe following are the various methods that can be used to assess the blood pressure reading:\n\nAmmeter  A device that measures the force of the blood flowing through the artery. The force of the blood depends on the elasticity of the artery wall, the elasticity of the blood itself, and the pressure on the artery. A small gauge (smaller than 5mm) is used to measure the blood pressure.\n\nAutomated monitor  A device that measures the blood pressure at several points in the arm, over a period of time.\n\nTracking blood pressure  An electronic device that measures the blood pressure throughout the day.\n\nWhat are the treatment options for high blood pressure?\n\nAchieving and maintaining a healthy blood pressure is important for your overall health. The following are the treatment options for high blood pressure:\n\nMedication\n\nMild to moderate high blood pressure can be treated with lifestyle changes, such as:\n\nExercise regularly\n\nEat a healthy diet\n\nReduce salt intake\n\nControl blood sugar levels\n\nTo reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease, you should also be checked for:\n\nDiet and weight\n\nSmoking\n\nDiabetes\n\nHigh blood pressure can be treated with medication.\n\nMedication is usually started at a moderate dosage, and is gradually increased, until it is at the desired blood pressure level.\n\nOver the longer term, the following medication is usually prescribed:\n\nBlood pressure medication\n\nHigh blood pressure medication should be prescribed by a doctor or nurse. The doctor or nurse will advise the appropriate dose and schedule.\n\nHigh blood pressure medication may be taken by mouth, injected into a vein, or administered as a patch.\n\nIf your blood pressure is too high, it may be necessary to use a combination of medication.\n\nHow is high blood pressure managed?\n\nIf your doctor has prescribed medication for high blood pressure, it is important to take the medication regularly.\n\nYour doctor will also check your blood pressure regularly, and may prescribe other medicines, such as:\n\nTreatments for high blood pressure may be covered by Medicare.\n\nIf you have questions about your health, or have concerns about your health, talk to your doctor, nurse or pharmacist.\n\nHow can I best manage my blood pressure?\n\nThe following are some tips to help you manage your blood pressure:\n\nMaintain a healthy body weight\n\nMaintain a healthy body weight\n\nA healthy body weight is an important part of good health. It can be achieved by eating a healthy diet and exercising regularly.\n\nEat a healthy diet\n\nEat a healthy diet\n\nEating a healthy diet is an important part of maintaining good health. A healthy diet has:\n\nA balance of fibre and protein\n\nGrains, vegetables and fruit\n\nFruit juices\n\nLean meats\n\nRed meat\n\nFruits and vegetables are rich'

Prompt: 'What lifestyle changes can help prevent and lower high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: "Here are some lifestyle changes you can make to help prevent high blood pressure:\n1. Eat less salt.\nThe Institute of Medicine recommends a maximum of 2,300 milligrams of sodium a day, or less than two teaspoons.\n2. Cut back on processed foods.\nThat includes hot dogs, soups, breakfast cereals, chips, crackers, and ready-to-eat foods.\n3. Get moving.\nTry to get 150 minutes of moderate-intensity activity a week, or 75 minutes of vigorous activity.\n4. Do less stress.\nThat includes managing your workload and setting limits on how many hours you spend in front of the TV.\n5. Cut back on alcohol.\nHave no more than one drink a day for women and two for men.\n6. Quit smoking.\nIt's a proven fact that smoking increases the risk of high blood pressure."

Prompt: 'What kind of medicines can help control high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nSome common medicines to help control high blood pressure include diuretics, beta-blockers and calcium channel blockers, according to WebMD. Some of these drugs are combined with a diuretic in a pill called a diuretic-beta blocker combination pill, while others are combined with a calcium channel blocker in a pill called a calcium channel blocker-beta blocker combination pill.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nDiuretics reduce the amount of water in the body, causing it to lose sodium and become more concentrated, notes the Mayo Clinic. Beta-blockers reduce the heart rate, which allows the heart to work more efficiently and reduces the amount of oxygen the heart has to use. Calcium channel blockers help relax the blood vessels, allowing more blood to move through them, according to WebMD.'

Prompt: 'What are some things that can increase the risk of getting high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nThe risk of getting high blood pressure can be increased through the consumption of junk food, smoking, not doing any physical activity, and being overweight, according to Mayo Clinic. These factors can also increase the risk of developing heart disease.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nConsuming excess salt and fat can lead to high blood pressure, according to Mayo Clinic. A high-fat diet can also increase the risk of developing diabetes, which increases the risk of high blood pressure, according to Mayo Clinic. They are caused by misfolding of normally harmless proteins, leading to the formation of a misfolded protein called a prion. But it doesnt cure the disease.\n\nIn addition, doctors can also treat CJD by using a drug called galactose-N-acetylglucosaminyl transferase inhibitor. Prompt: 'What are the types of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nIn Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, amyloid deposits form in the brain and spinal cord, and it is characterized by symptoms such as dementia, muscle weakness, abnormal behaviour and abnormal mental status.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nCreutzfeldt-Jakob disease is an inherited neurodegenerative disease, which means it is caused by a mutation in a gene. People inherit two copies of the gene from each parent, and each one of these copies can contain one or two mutations.\n\nPeople with one mutated copy of the gene, which is inherited from their father, are at risk of developing Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. The risk of developing this condition is greater if the mutated copy is inherited from the mother because a child inherits two copies of the gene from both parents.\n\nPeople with two mutated copies of the gene are considered to have two separate types of the disease. The two types are sporadic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is a sporadic form of the disease, and familial Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is a family form of the disease.\n\nThe two types of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease are considered to be quite different because the symptoms of the two types vary. For example, people with sporadic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease usually develop signs of dementia and mental decline after the age of 50. This is not the case with people with the familial form of the disease, who develop signs of the disease early in life.'

Prompt: 'What are the symptoms of multiple sclerosis?\n' 
Generated text: '\nMore than one-quarter of cases of multiple sclerosis, also known as MS, are unknown to doctors.\n\nHow do I know if I have multiple sclerosis?\n\nIf you have any of the following symptoms, you may have MS:\n\nPain and numbness in your arms, legs, or face.\n\nSudden, sharp pain in your head or neck.\n\nVision problems, such as blurred or double vision.\n\nFeeling of warmth or tingling in your arms or legs.\n\nLeg pain, trouble walking, or falling.\n\nYou may also have more than one of these symptoms. Some people have more symptoms than others.\n\nWhat is MS?\n\nMultiple sclerosis (MS) is an autoimmune disease that affects your central nervous system (brain, spinal cord, and nerves). The immune system attacks and inflames the protective myelin sheath that coats your nerves. This damages the nerves and disrupts your ability to control your muscles, including your vision and balance.\n\nMS is an unpredictable disease that affects people of all ages and races. It is more common in young adults and women than in men.\n\nWhat causes multiple sclerosis?\n\nScientists dont know the cause of MS, but they think several factors contribute. Some of these factors are inherited. In some families, it is more common for someone to develop MS than in others.\n\nOther risk factors are related to your general health. For example, smoking, poor nutrition, and being overweight can make you more likely to have MS.\n\nWhat are the symptoms of multiple sclerosis?\n\nMS can cause a wide variety of symptoms. Many of these symptoms get better over time. If you have the first few symptoms, it may take time for your doctor to confirm the diagnosis of MS.\n\nIn some people, symptoms may be mild and be very difficult to recognize. Some people with MS have mild symptoms that only show up when theyre under stress. Others have more severe symptoms that are easier to recognize.\n\nOther symptoms may come and go. For example, some people have mild symptoms for months or even years before they get worse. Some people with MS may have no symptoms at all.\n\nHow is multiple sclerosis diagnosed?\n\nTo confirm a diagnosis of MS, your doctor may ask you to do certain tests and then look at your medical history and symptoms. You may also have a series of tests to help confirm your diagnosis.\n\nYour doctor may do the following tests:\n\nMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scan. This test uses a strong magnetic field to help show the structure of your brain and spinal cord.\n\nElectroencephalography (EEG). This test records the electrical activity of the brain. It is used to help diagnose MS or help find out if MS is causing any problems with your nervous system.\n\nFunctional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI). This test uses a magnet to measure how well your brain is working. It is used to help diagnose MS or to see if MS is causing any problems with your nervous system.\n\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis. This test measures the amount of fluid in the brain and spinal cord.\n\nBlood tests. These tests measure your levels of proteins and other substances in your blood. They are used to help confirm the diagnosis of MS or to help find out if MS is causing any problems with your nervous system.\n\nA neurologist, or doctor who specializes in the diagnosis and treatment of nervous system disorders, may also do a brain biopsy. This involves drilling a hole in the skull to take a sample of brain tissue.\n\nHow is multiple sclerosis treated?\n\nThere is no cure for MS. Treatment is aimed at relieving symptoms and slowing the progression of the disease.\n\nYour doctor will probably give you an MS medication. This medication may help control your symptoms and slow the progression of the disease. Some medications can even prevent the progression of the disease.\n\nOther treatments may include:\n\nPhysical therapy. Physical therapists can help you with muscle and balance problems caused by MS. They can also help you strengthen your muscles and improve your posture.\n\nSpeech, language, and swallowing therapy. Speech and language specialists can help you with speech problems and other swallowing problems caused by MS. They can also teach you ways to eat, drink, and swallow safely.\n\nOccupational therapy. Generated text: "Multiple sclerosis is an autoimmune disease that can cause numbness, pain, vision problems and fatigue, among other symptoms.\nThe disease is so complex that it's often difficult to pinpoint the exact cause. However, doctors have narrowed it down to some of the most common theories.\nA new study suggests that a mix of genetic, environmental and viral factors are to blame.\nThe new study, published in the journal Nature Genetics, revealed that the MS genes of people with the disease are more likely to be mutated.\nResearchers also discovered that the genes of the people who have the disease are more likely to interact with other genes in the body.\nThis combination is known as a genetic network.\nThe researchers found that the MS genes were associated with both 'positive' and 'negative' interactions.\n'Positive' interactions mean that the gene affects the body in a positive way - in other words, it helps the body function.\n'Negative' interactions mean that the gene affects the body in a negative way - for example, it causes a disease.\nA new study has revealed that the MS genes of people with the disease are more likely to be mutated. This combination is known as a genetic network. A stock image is pictured\nAnother key discovery was that MS genes are more likely to be mutated in people who have the disease.\nThis is in contrast to studies where researchers found that the genes of people without the disease were more likely to be mutated.\nThese differences were explained by the researchers, who said that the MS genes of people with the disease are 'extremely frequently mutated'.\n'This suggests that the MS genetic landscape is more complex than previously appreciated,' said the researchers.\nHowever, the researchers were unable to determine which exact MS gene is mutated in people with the disease.\nA study from last year revealed that a toxic protein found in the brain is a major factor in MS.\nThe protein, called C1q, affects the growth of blood vessels and is linked to MS.\nAdditionally, other studies have pointed to the existence of a virus called 'Listeria monocytogenes' in MS patients.\nThe virus - which was first discovered in the 19th century - can cause inflammation and can also trigger MS.\nThe immune system's natural defence system, called T cells, is also thought to be involved in MS.\nThe discovery that a toxic protein found in the brain is a major factor in MS could lead to new treatment options, according to experts. Prompt: 'What is the outlook for people with multiple sclerosis?\n' 
Generated text: "\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nThe outlook for people with multiple sclerosis is good, according to Dr. Susan H. Haig, a neurologist at the Medical College of Georgia. People with multiple sclerosis may develop complications such as pneumonia, stroke or Alzheimer's disease.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nPeople with multiple sclerosis have a 30 percent chance of developing cancer in their lifetime, according to the Multiple Sclerosis Foundation. MS is the most common neurological disease in young adults in the United States. Symptoms typically appear in the 20s and 30s, but in rare cases, symptoms appear in adolescence or adulthood.\n\nA person's risk of developing MS increases if a family member has the condition, according to the National Multiple Sclerosis Society. Smoking and obesity are associated with a higher risk of developing MS. Certain types of infections, smoking, head injuries and viral infections are also associated with an increased risk of MS.\n\nAccording to the Multiple Sclerosis Foundation, MS can be treated effectively if symptoms are caught early. Symptoms may include visual problems, fatigue and bladder problems. Treatment usually focuses on decreasing muscle weakness, improving mobility and controlling symptoms. Medications may be prescribed to treat vision problems and pain.\n\nTreatment for MS is not curative, but it may slow the progression of the disease and improve quality of life. The most common treatment is a drug called interferon, which attacks the immune system and may slow the progression of the disease. Other medications may be prescribed to treat vision problems, bladder problems, pain and other symptoms.\n\nMultiple sclerosis can also be treated with immunosuppressive medications, which suppress the immune system to help prevent the disease from worsening, according to the Multiple Sclerosis Foundation.\n\nA combination of therapies is the most effective treatment for people with relapsing remitting MS. People who are new to MS treatment should start with the lowest dose possible. Multiple sclerosis treatments typically last for several years."

Prompt: 'What are some of the risk factors of high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: "\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nThere are three risk factors that can lead to high blood pressure: obesity, smoking and genetics, according to WebMD. The risk of high blood pressure can increase with age. In fact, only 17 percent of adults over the age of 20 and 23 percent of those over the age of 60 have high blood pressure, according to the Mayo Clinic.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nObesity, high cholesterol and a lack of physical activity are risk factors for high blood pressure, according to WebMD. High cholesterol is a condition in which the body does not produce enough cholesterol. A lack of physical activity causes the body to become overweight or obese. This results in high blood pressure.\n\nThe presence of high blood pressure in a person's family is also a risk factor for high blood pressure, according to WebMD. People with family members who have high blood pressure are more likely to have high blood pressure themselves. High blood pressure can also be a risk factor for other conditions."

Prompt: 'Is it possible to check blood pressure at home?\n' 
Generated text: "\nYes, there are a few ways you can take your blood pressure at home.\n\nThe two most common ways to take your blood pressure are with a blood pressure cuff and a device that uses a light pulse to measure your pulse.\n\nBlood pressure devices can be purchased online and at retail stores. They range in price from about $50 to $200.\n\nThere are also many blood pressure cuffs available at a variety of drug stores, ranging in price from $10 to $50.\n\nBefore taking your blood pressure, it's important to consult your doctor. Your doctor will assess the health of your blood vessels to make sure you're not at risk for heart disease, and may recommend other tests for your health.\n\nHow do you take your blood pressure at home?\n\nTo take your blood pressure at home, follow these steps:\n\nStand up.\n\nPlace your hands on your upper arm, at the back of the shoulder blades.\n\nStretch the top of the cuff over your upper arm to allow it to fit comfortably.\n\nFasten the cuff by pressing the large red or black button.\n\nRemove the cuff by pressing the same button.\n\nRemove the device by sliding it off the back of your arm.\n\nTake your blood pressure by squeezing the cuff.\n\nHow should your blood pressure be measured?\n\nYour blood pressure should be measured as close to the center of your arm as possible.\n\nYour doctor will show you how to take your blood pressure and will teach you how to interpret the results.\n\nHow often should you take your blood pressure?\n\nBlood pressure is checked each time you visit your doctor. Blood pressure is checked before you have a test, such as a physical or an x-ray, and after you have a test.\n\nHow much information should you get from your blood pressure?\n\nYour blood pressure is a measure of the force that moves blood around your body. The lower your blood pressure, the better your health.\n\nBlood pressure readings can be higher in some people. For instance, your blood pressure may be higher when you are:\n\nstanding up than when you're sitting down\n\nwalking than when you're lying down\n\nbreathing than when you're not\n\nThe average blood pressure reading is around 120/80. If your blood pressure is higher than 120/80, it may be due to:\n\nthe stress of a medical test\n\nthe stress of a medical test if you have a problem with your heart or blood vessels\n\nHowever, if your blood pressure reading is higher than 140/90, your doctor will likely order other tests, such as an echocardiogram, to see if you have a problem with your heart or blood vessels.\n\nIf your blood pressure is lower than 80/60, it may be due to:\n\nhigh blood pressure\n\nhigh blood pressure if you have a problem with your heart or blood vessels\n\nIf your blood pressure is very low, your doctor will probably perform a rapid-acting treatment, such as an injection or a pill.\n\nBlood pressure is not an exact measure of heart health. Instead, it's a rough estimate of your overall health and the health of your heart.\n\nMedications may be prescribed to help lower your blood pressure. These medications may include a diuretic, which makes your urine more concentrated; an ACE inhibitor, which helps your heart relax and may help lower your blood pressure; or a beta blocker, which helps relax your heart and may help lower your blood pressure.\n\nIt's important to follow your doctor's instructions for taking your medications. If you miss a dose or take your medication at a different time than you're supposed to, your blood pressure may not be as low as it should be.\n\nCheck your blood pressure\n\nIf you have high blood pressure, your doctor will likely recommend that you start taking medications to lower your blood pressure.\n\nYour doctor may also refer you to a cardiologist for evaluation.\n\nIf you have low blood pressure, you may need to start taking medications to raise your blood pressure.\n\nIf your blood pressure is very low, your doctor may recommend that you start taking diuretics or oxygen. You may also need to see a cardiologist.\n\nBlood pressure cuffs\n\nThe American Heart Association recommends that you use a home blood pressure monitor to measure your blood pressure. Your doctor may recommend that you use a blood pressure cuff.\n\nWhat are the benefits of using a blood pressure cuff?\n\nThe benefits of using a blood pressure cuff are:\n\nYou can check your blood pressure at home.\n\nYou can check your blood pressure with or without medication.\n\nYou can check your blood pressure without the need for a medical office visit.\n\nYou can check your blood pressure using a blood pressure cuff.\n\nThe downside to using a blood pressure cuff is that it's difficult to use."

Prompt: 'What are some of the health conditions that high blood pressure can lead to?\n' 
Generated text: "\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nHigh blood pressure can lead to a host of health problems, including heart disease, heart attack, heart failure, stroke and kidney disease, according to MedlinePlus. High blood pressure can lead to damage to the nerves in the brain, which can cause blurry vision, dizziness and pain.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nHigh blood pressure can also damage the heart's arteries and veins, potentially leading to heart attacks, heart failure and stroke, according to MedlinePlus. High blood pressure can also cause damage to the kidneys, which can lead to kidney failure and kidney disease. According to the Mayo Clinic, high blood pressure can also damage the eyes and the skin. High blood pressure can make the eyes water, causing a feeling of pressure and pain in the eyes, and can cause skin to look red, dry and itchy."

Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nBronchiolitis is an infection of the respiratory passages caused by bacteria, viruses or fungi, and it most commonly affects infants under 12 months of age, older children, teenagers and adults with chronic lung conditions, according to the Mayo Clinic. Symptoms include a hacking cough, sore throat, sneezing, runny nose, wheezing and difficulty breathing.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nChildren with bronchiolitis have a reduced ability to breathe and are more likely to have a fever, according to the Mayo Clinic. Symptoms may worsen over time, and a severe case may cause wheezing, shortness of breath, chest pain, cough that produces blood and other signs of pneumonia. Bronchiolitis is often accompanied by a cold, and it is treated with antibiotics.\n\nChronic bronchitis is an inflammation of the bronchi, which are the tubes that bring air from the lungs into the trachea. The inflammation is caused by mucus and other material in the airway that is trapped and inflammation. Bronchitis causes shortness of breath, chest pain and coughing, and it is often accompanied by a persistent cold. Treatment with antibiotics is typically prescribed.\n\nSymptoms of bronchiolitis are similar to those of chronic bronchitis. However, a child with chronic bronchitis may have no wheezing, no cough and no fever.'

Bronchiolitis is the inflammation of the small airways that lead to the lungs. Symptoms of bronchiolitis include fever, cough, wheezing, chest pain and shortness of breath.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nIf symptoms are not severe, WebMD recommends a restful night's sleep and the use of over-the-counter cough medicines. If symptoms worsen, such as difficulty breathing, chest tightness or chest pain, WebMD recommends taking ibuprofen or acetaminophen to relieve symptoms. If symptoms are severe enough, WebMD recommends calling a physician or 911.\n\nWhen severe symptoms are present, such as difficulty breathing, WebMD recommends the use of an inhaler or nebulizer to deliver oxygen directly to the lungs, which will ease symptoms. A nebulizer delivers medication to the lungs through an aerosol spray. Some medications, such as steroids, can relieve bronchiolitis symptoms."

women.\n\nBut some are more common in men.\n\nThese include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, high blood sugar and obesity.\n\nMen are also more likely to have a heart attack after a major illness such as a heart attack, stroke or a heart valve problem.\n\nMen are also more likely to have a heart attack after a major illness such as a heart attack, stroke or a heart valve problem\n\nHowever, women are more likely to have a heart attack as a result of high blood pressure, high cholesterol and diabetes.\n\nWhat are the symptoms of a stroke?\n\nA stroke is an injury to the blood vessels that supply blood to the brain.\n\nThey can either be ischaemic (a blockage in one of the blood vessels in the brain) or haemorrhagic (a bleeding into the brain).\n\nThe symptoms of a stroke are similar in men and women, but men will usually experience a sudden onset of weakness on one side of the body.\n\nHowever, women may have:\n\nDifficulty speaking\n\nSeeing or feeling people and objects that are not there\n\nUnable to move the affected side of the body\n\nIt can be difficult to identify the signs and symptoms of a stroke as they are often the same as those of a heart attack.\n\nIf you notice you are struggling to speak or move, call 999 or go to the nearest hospital.\n\nWhat are the symptoms of a heart attack in children?\n\nChildren can also have a heart neck, jaw or back\n\nFeeling sick or throwing up\n\nChildren can also have a heart attack, but they are not likely to show the same symptoms as adults\n\nThe symptoms of a heart attack in children will usually be different to those in adults and they will be more likely to be caused by a viral infection.\n\nCall 999 if you notice your child struggling to speak or move their limbs, and go to the Emergency care includes immediate treatment to restore blood flow, oxygen and nutrients to the heart, and to keep blood pressure and heart rate normal.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nEmergency care includes IV fluids and blood thinners if the patient is at risk of bleeding, according to the Mayo Clinic. Medical doctors may place a stent in the coronary arteries, if the heart attack is due to blocked blood vessels.\n\nHeart medications, such as ACE inhibitors and beta blockers, are also important in treating heart attacks. These medications help open the coronary arteries and reduce the risk of a heart attack, according to the Mayo Clinic. The American Heart Association explains that the medication nifedipine is the only drug approved by the Food and Drug Administration to improve blood flow to the heart. The American Heart Association also recommends medications such as glyburide, verapamil and dobutamine for patients with low blood pressure.'

People with bronchiolitis may experience a dry cough, difficulty breathing, and frequent chest infections. The chest pain and pressure caused by bronchiolitis may radiate to the shoulders and back. Doctors may prescribe antibiotics and other medicines to treat bronchiolitis.\n\nIn some cases, a person may develop scarring and permanent lung damage. Scarring occurs when the bronchial tubes close up after the infection has gone away. The damage may cause the lung to be weaker and less effective at the oxygen-carrying work that it does.'

Prompt: 'What is Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n' 
Generated text: '\nCreutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) is a rare, fatal, progressive, degenerative brain disease caused by an abnormal protein called prion. The prion protein clumps together and can be transferred from one cell to another, leading to an abnormal build-up of this protein in the brain.\n\nThere is no cure for CJD. Patients usually die within 18 months of symptoms starting.\n\nWhat causes Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n\nThe abnormal prion protein CJD is caused by an abnormal gene (the gene for the prion protein).\n\nThere are many different ways of acquiring the abnormal gene. This may be because of:\n\ninfection\n\ninheritance\n\nmutation\n\ntransmutation\n\nWhat are the symptoms of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n\nPeople with CJD may suffer from:\n\nconfusion\n\nproblems with thinking and memory\n\nvomiting\n\ndifficulty swallowing\n\nheadaches\n\nseizures\n\nexcessive drooling\n\nblindness\n\nnumbness and tingling\n\nrapid loss of muscle control\n\nchanges in consciousness\n\nchanges in behaviour\n\nBefore these changes develop, people with CJD may show no symptoms.\n\nIn most cases, the first sign of the disease is a change in personality. If you think a family member or friend may have CJD, discuss this with your doctor, as there is no early screening test.\n\nWhen and where is Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease found?\n\nCJD is more commonly found in people over the age of 65. However, cases of CJD have been seen in people of all ages.\n\nCJD can be found in the United Kingdom, in Europe, in Africa and in South America.\n\nCJD can also be found in people with a very rare genetic condition called spongiform encephalopathy.\n\nTreatment\n\nThere is no cure for Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, and there is no treatment that can slow its progress. Treatment aims to relieve symptoms and the pain and suffering of people with the condition.\n\nThe symptoms of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease are usually severe and progressive. As the disease gets worse, people will often be confined to a wheelchair.\n\nDoctors can give medicines to help relieve symptoms and pain.\n\nEvaluation and diagnosis of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease\n\nA doctor can diagnose CJD if they suspect it on the basis of:\n\nclinical symptoms\n\nneurological examination\n\nfinding abnormal protein in the brain (echogenic plaques)\n\nfinding abnormal protein in the spinal fluid (spinal fluid lymphocyte aggregates)\n\nfinding abnormal protein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)\n\nIf you think a family member or friend may have CJD, discuss this with your doctor, as there is no early screening test.\n\nIf you have been diagnosed with CJD, or are concerned that you may have the disease, you should seek medical advice.\n\nThis page contains information about Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that has been extracted from publicly available material. Prompt: 'What is iatrogenic CJD?\n' 
Generated text: '\nIatrogenic CJD (iatrogenic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease) is a rare, fatal, human disease caused by a human retrovirus (human endogenous retrovirus, HERV). Iatrogenic CJD occurs when a person is given the retroviral immunoglobulin G (IgG) or immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies to protect against a different disease (such as an infection). Such therapy was once common. Over the last decade, however, few people receive these antibodies.\n\nThe iatrogenic form of CJD is a rare variant, in which the iatrogenic antibodies cross the bloodbrain barrier and cause damage to the brain. There is no evidence that the iatrogenic form of CJD is caused by any other human retrovirus. The main risk factors for iatrogenic CJD are the use of recombinant human insulin (human insulin gene transfer) for diabetes, and the use of human insulin or human insulin gene transfer for any other disease.\n\nSymptoms\n\nThe iatrogenic form of CJD can cause any of the following symptoms:\n\nA slight loss of balance or gait may be present\n\nLoss of muscle coordination, balance, or coordination of facial expression may be present\n\nA very slight loss of muscle tone and rigidity of limbs may be present.\n\nThere may be a slight loss of bladder control.\n\nThere may be a slight loss of coordination of facial expression.\n\nPrognosis\n\nThe iatrogenic form of CJD is a rapidly progressive disease with a poor prognosis. Death usually occurs within 1 to 3 years of diagnosis. Generated text: "\nCJD is a fatal neurological disease caused by a brain infection called bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE).\n\nCJD is a transmissible, incurable, and always fatal disease.\n\nA small percentage of people with CJD develop a form of the disease known as Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD-d), and CJD-d can be treated with intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG).\n\nCJD-d is caused by an abnormality in the prion protein of the brain, which is also found in people with CJD.\n\nA person with CJD-d may have a short time to live, but IVIG treatment can slow or stop the progress of the disease.\n\nCJD-d is treated by a series of infusions of intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) given over a period of several months.\n\nA normal prion protein in the brain is important for the normal functioning of nerve cells.\n\nHowever, an abnormality in the prion protein of the brain is associated with the development of transmissible spongiform encephalopathies such as CJD.\n\nA person with CJD-d has a genetic abnormality in the prion protein that may be inherited.\n\nSince CJD is a brain disease, treatment may include medications to treat depression, anxiety, and sleep disorders.\n\nTreatment may also include specialized surgical procedures and devices to treat the person's condition.\n\nComplications of CJD\n\nComplications of CJD include dementia, depression, and other neurological problems.\n\nPrognosis\n\nA person with CJD may have a short time to live, but IVIG treatment can slow or stop the progress of the disease.\n\nSome people with CJD may be able to control the disease with medication. This can lead to a sudden loss of blood flow to the heart muscle and possibly death.\n\nThe heart is made up of four chambers, or chambers. Two of the chambers - the left and right atrium - pump blood into the lungs. The left atrium receives oxygen-rich blood from the lungs and pumps it into the left ventricle. Prompt: 'What are the complications of a heart attack?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nAccording to the Mayo Clinic, the most common complication of a heart attack is permanent heart damage. A heart attack can lead to heart failure, which means that the heart muscle can no longer pump enough blood to the rest of the body, and it can also cause angina, or chest pain. Other common complications include a heart attack-related disability, congestive heart failure and heart attack-related death.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nHeart attacks can be serious, even if they do not cause death. A heart attack can be a life-threatening condition, and it is important to seek treatment as soon as possible. The Mayo Clinic advises that signs of a heart attack include pain or discomfort in the center of the chest that lasts more than a few minutes, discomfort in one or both arms, back or jaw, shortness of breath or coughing up blood. The Mayo Clinic also notes that people with chest pain may have other symptoms, such as nausea, lightheadedness, sweating, indigestion or back pain.\n\nThe most effective treatment for heart attacks is to open up the coronary artery and restore blood flow. Treatment options include angioplasty and stenting, and the American Heart Association notes that these procedures are highly effective for treating heart attacks. The Mayo Clinic notes that stents can be placed in the coronary artery to reinforce or widen the artery.\n\nOther treatment options include medications, such as beta blockers and calcium channel blockers. The Mayo Clinic notes that beta blockers may be recommended for people who have heart failure. Other options include the use of angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors, which are also available in combination with a calcium channel blocker.'

The lining of the heart is made up of many tiny blood vessels. The heart muscle is lined with a soft connective tissue called myocardium.\n\nWhen a heart attack occurs, the blood supply to the left side of the heart is blocked. The heart muscle is starved of oxygen-rich blood and begins to die. If the blockage is severe, the heart muscle can die, and if the blockage is not severe, the heart muscle can grow weaker.\n\nThe heart muscle can be healed by surgery, but in most cases, the heart will have to be replaced with a mechanical heart.\n\nMany heart attacks are caused by the build-up of fatty deposits known as plaque. The Heart & Vascular Center team of cardiologists, cardiac surgeons, vascular surgeons, and nurses is one of the best in the world at treating heart attacks.\n\nDuring a heart attack, blood flow to the heart is cut off by a blood clot. The heart is starved of oxygen-rich blood, and the heart muscle begins to die. This can be fatal.\n\nThe blockage in the artery can be opened by removing the blood clot, which is done by means of catheterization. The catheter is placed into the artery and directed to the blockage. A balloon is then inflated, causing the blood clot to break up and the blockage to be removed.\n\nSurgery can be used to reopen the artery. Prompt: 'What are corticosteroids?\n' 
Generated text: "\nCorticosteroids are a group of medications that lower the body's ability to make its own inflammatory chemicals. Corticosteroids are used to treat a variety of conditions. They may be used alone or in combination with other medications.\n\nThe most common corticosteroid is prednisone. Corticosteroid medications may also be used to treat chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), psoriasis, eczema, allergic rhinitis, and severe asthma.\n\nCorticosteroids may also be used for purposes not listed in this medication guide.\n\nHow should I use corticosteroids?\n\nCorticosteroids should be used only if your doctor has prescribed them. Do not use corticosteroids if you are pregnant. It is not known if corticosteroids are effective in treating certain infections, but they may increase the risk of infection in you or your baby.\n\nYour doctor may have you take corticosteroids before or after an operation.\n\nBefore you take corticosteroids, tell your doctor about all of your medical conditions, especially if you:\n\nhave been told you may be allergic to corticosteroids\n\nhave an ulcer\n\nare taking any prescription or nonprescription drugs\n\nare using any other medications\n\nhave or are going to have surgery\n\nhave or are going to have surgery in your stomach or esophagus\n\nHow should I store corticosteroids?\n\nKeep corticosteroids out of the reach of children.\n\nDo not store corticosteroids in the bathroom. Heat or moisture may cause them to break down.\n\nKeep corticosteroids away from other medications. Do not use them together.\n\nStore corticosteroids at room temperature, away from moisture, heat, and direct light.\n\nWhat happens if I miss a dose?\n\nTake your next dose at the regular time. Prompt: 'What is HIV?\n' 
Generated text: '\nHIV, or Human Immunodeficiency Virus, is a virus that attacks the immune system. It has an envelope around it that is so tough that it is impossible to break through. The virus attacks white blood cells, and can cause diseases such as AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome) and lymphoma. Once it is in the bloodstream, it may spread to the nervous system, brain, liver and spleen.\n\nPeople who have AIDS have many illnesses due to the virus. Some of the most common symptoms are weight loss, fever, sores in the mouth and throat, stomach pain, and weakness. With HIV, there is a strong possibility that the immune system will begin to fail, and the person may have a high risk of developing tuberculosis, hepatitis, pneumonia, and cancer.\n\nHIV can be transmitted through blood and bodily fluids, including semen, vaginal fluid, breast milk and saliva. Transmission can occur if an infected person does not know that he or she is infected.\n\nHIV cannot be spread through casual contact. In order to transmit HIV, a person must have a break in their immune system. It is important to note that HIV is not the cause of AIDS. AIDS is caused by the body\'s immune system becoming weak and unable to fight off a wide variety of infections.\n\nPeople can be infected with HIV if they have sex with someone who is infected with the virus. This is known as "contact" transmission. The virus can also be transmitted if someone has sex with an infected mother and her child is born with HIV.\n\nWhat are the symptoms of HIV?\n\nSome of the first symptoms of HIV are flu-like, and include fever, chills, sore throat, and muscle aches. Prompt: 'What are the symptoms of multiple sclerosis?\n' 
Generated text: '\nMS symptoms can appear suddenly or gradually, as in progressive MS. The most common symptoms of MS are:\n\nVision problems, including blurriness or loss of vision in one or both eyes, double vision or a feeling of being "tunnel-visioned".\n\nTingling, numbness or pain in the hands, legs or feet.\n\nBalance problems that make it difficult to walk, stand or balance.\n\nHow is multiple sclerosis diagnosed?\n\nA neurologist will review your symptoms and perform a physical exam. He or she will also order blood tests and other tests, including:\n\nBlood tests to measure levels of the antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody, or ANCA. If these levels are high, they may indicate that you have autoimmune disease.\n\nCT scan to see if the brain has lesions.\n\nMRI scan of the brain to look for lesions.\n\nHow is multiple sclerosis treated?\n\nTreatment varies depending on the severity of your symptoms. Some people take drugs, such as beta interferon or interleukin-2, to treat symptoms. Others may need to take medication for the rest of their lives.\n\nSome people have other treatments, including:\n\nMuscle-relaxing drugs\n\nPhysical therapy to increase flexibility and strength\n\nNerve damage treatment, including spinal cord stimulation or deep brain stimulation\n\nStem cell transplants are sometimes used to treat MS.\n\nWhat are the risks of multiple sclerosis?\n\nMultiple sclerosis is the most common neurological disease of young adults in the United States. Although it is more common in women, it can affect men as well. The risk of developing MS increases as people age.\n\nRisk factors for multiple sclerosis include:\n\nFamily history.\n\nWomen who are pregnant or breast-feeding.\n\nSmoking and being exposed to secondhand smoke.\n\nHaving an autoimmune disorder, such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis.\n\nHaving the disease-causing gene called the B-cell lymphoma 2 gene.\n\nWhat is the prognosis of multiple sclerosis?\n\nThe overall prognosis for people with MS depends on the severity and location of the disease.\n\nMS symptoms can worsen and become more severe over time. As the disease progresses, your brain can become more sensitive to light, causing you to have headaches, blurred vision, dizziness or double vision. The progression of MS can also cause severe disability, particularly if the disease affects the brain.\n\nIf your symptoms are mild, you may be able to live a full and active life, although you may need some physical therapy to help you stay mobile and flexible. You may need to learn to live with the effects of MS, such as walking with a cane or sitting in a wheelchair.\n\nIf the disease affects your brain, you may develop progressive MS. This type of MS can result in worsening disability and paralysis, and may lead to death.\n\nProgression of multiple sclerosis can be slowed or stopped through medication. If you continue to take your medications, your symptoms may improve.\n\nIf you have relapsing-remitting MS, your symptoms can get better over time, or get worse, or stay the same. The course of your disease depends on the severity of your symptoms.\n\nIn contrast, if you have primary progressive MS, the disease worsens over time.\n\nWhat are the complications of multiple sclerosis?\n\nComplications of MS include:\n\nNeurological damage.\n\nVisual problems, including blindness.\n\nUncontrolled pain.\n\nHow can multiple sclerosis be prevented?\n\nIn the past, researchers thought the best way to prevent multiple sclerosis was to avoid exposure to certain viruses, such as rubella and measles. However, research has shown that these viruses do not cause the disease.\n\nExperts still believe that multiple sclerosis is caused by an autoimmune disorder, such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis, but researchers have not yet determined what causes these conditions.\n\nThere is no way to prevent MS. However, a healthy lifestyle may lower your risk of MS. A healthy diet and lifestyle can lower your risk of developing other health problems, too.'

Prompt: 'What causes multiple sclerosis?\n' 
Generated text: '\nMultiple sclerosis is a chronic inflammatory demyelinating disorder that affects the brain and spinal cord. Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic inflammatory demyelinating disorder of the central nervous system (CNS) and is caused by a previously unidentified autoimmune disease.\n\nMultiple sclerosis (MS) is one of the most common chronic inflammatory demyelinating disorders of the central nervous system (CNS). It has three types of symptoms: relapsing, remitting, and progressive forms. Relapsing forms are the most common type and can be classified as primary or secondary. Primary relapsing forms of MS are initially diagnosed before a person reaches 40 years of age, while secondary relapsing forms are more common in older patients.\n\nThe majority of patients will have two or more relapses in their life time, which can range from one to five. A relapse is a temporary worsening of symptoms that occurs after a remission. There are two types of remitting forms of MS: primary and secondary. Primary remitting forms can be either primary or secondary. Secondary forms of MS are more likely to progress into secondary progressive forms of MS.\n\nThe progressive forms of MS are most common in women and people who are under age 40. The progressive forms of MS can cause gradual loss of cognitive function and can also lead to paralysis. The causes of progressive forms are unknown, although smoking, family history of multiple sclerosis, and exposure to environmental factors such as ultraviolet radiation have been associated with the disease.\n\nMultiple sclerosis can also develop as a result of spinal cord injury. It can also occur as a result of stroke or trauma.\n\nIf multiple sclerosis occurs in the brain, it is known as brain-specific MS (BSMS). If it occurs in the spinal cord, it is known as spinal cord-specific MS (SCMS). If both brain and spinal cord are affected, it is called mixed-type MS.\n\nMost of the time, multiple sclerosis is diagnosed in the early stages of the disease. The early stages of MS occur when the person has one to three relapses. It can take up to seven years for the disease to progress from the early to the middle stages.\n\nIn the middle stages of MS, the disease will progress to the severe form of MS. In the severe form, the person will have at least two relapses and there will be cognitive impairment. The progressive forms of MS can cause gradual loss of cognitive function and can also lead to paralysis. The causes of progressive forms are unknown, although smoking, family history of multiple sclerosis, and exposure to environmental factors such as ultraviolet radiation have been associated with the disease.\n\nMultiple sclerosis can also develop as a result of spinal cord injury. It can also occur as a result of stroke or trauma.\n\nIf multiple sclerosis occurs in the brain, it is known as brain-specific MS (BSMS). If it occurs in the spinal cord, it is known as spinal cord-specific MS (SCMS). If both brain and spinal cord are affected, it is called mixed-type MS.\n\nMost of the time, multiple sclerosis is diagnosed in the early stages of the disease.
